Get rich quick $$

Introduction

Today, Ill be attempting to use two datasets from Kaggle, the first being a Reddit news dataset containing the top 25 daily headlines from Reddit WorldNews Channel (/r/worldnews) from 2008-2016. The second dataset contains the opening and closing values of the DOW Jones Index for the same period of 2008-2016. My goal for the project is to use Natural Language Processing techniques to predict whether the stock market will rise or fall based on the headlines for a particular day.

Preprocessing

Lets read in our data from the CSV files from Kaggle.

First, lets join both tables based on the date so that we have one table to work with.

dow$Date <- as.Date(dow$Date)
news$Date <- as.Date(news$Date)

data <- merge(dow, news, by = "Date")

Now that we have our data in one table, lets go ahead and combine all of the top 25 headlines into one text blob.

data$all <- paste(data$Top1, data$Top2, data$Top3, data$Top4, data$Top5, data$Top6,
                  data$Top7, data$Top8, data$Top9, data$Top10, data$Top11, data$Top12, 
                  data$Top13, data$Top14, data$Top15, data$Top16, data$Top17, data$Top18,
                  data$Top19, data$Top20, data$Top21, data$Top22, data$Top23, data$Top24,
                  data$Top25, sep=' <s> ')

# Remove punctuations from text
data$all <- gsub('b"|b\'|\\\\|\\"', "", data$all)
data$all <- gsub("([<>])|[[:punct:]]", "\\1", data$all)

Now that we have our headline text data as wed like, lets go ahead and calculate the difference between the closing and opening price on the DOW index for a given day.

# Calculate the difference between the closing and opening index for a given day
data$Delta <- dow$Close - dow$Open

Now, lets throw away all the data that we dont need.

data <- data[, c('Date', 'all', 'Delta', 'Label')]

Note that there is a column called Label in which a 1 indicates that the Dow Jones index stayed the same or rose for a given day, and a 0 indicates that the Dow Jones index fell.

Well have to find a way to split up our data into a training and testing set. Lets have a look at the range of our dates. In order to do this, lets try to partition our dataset into a 75-25 train/test set.

training_data <- sample_frac(data, 0.75)
data$train_id = ifelse(data$Date %in% training_data$Date, "train", "test")

Building a glmnet model

Lets take all of the words the combined texts, tokenize them and put them into a matrix.

token_list <- tokenize_words(data$all)
token_df <- term_list_to_df(token_list)

X <- term_df_to_matrix(token_df, min_df = 0.05, max_df = 1, scale = FALSE)
y <- data$Delta

X_train <- X[data$train_id == "train",]
X_valid <- X[data$train_id == "test",]
y_train <- y[data$train_id == "train"]
y_valid <- y[data$train_id == "test"]

Finall, using glmnet lets construct our model.

library(glmnet)
## Loading required package: foreach
## Loaded glmnet 2.0-13
model <- cv.glmnet(X_train, y_train)
plot(model)

Lets predict values and see what accuracy we end up with.

data$Delta_pred <- predict(model, newx = X, type = "response", s=model$lambda[30])
#tapply(data$Label_pred == data$Label, data$train_id, mean)
sqrt(tapply((data$Delta_pred - data$Delta)^2, data$train_id, mean))
##      test     train 
## 183.31015  84.94153

We get an RMSE of ~180 using tokenization. Lets have a look at the other models get us.

Using bi-grams

Lets use bigrams to see if we can get a better prediction rate.

token_list <- tokenize_ngrams(data$all, n_min = 1, n = 2)
token_df <- term_list_to_df(token_list)
X <- term_df_to_matrix(token_df, min_df = 0.01, max_df = 0.90, scale = TRUE)
y <- data$Delta
X_train <- X[data$train_id == "train",]
X_valid <- X[data$train_id == "test",]
y_train <- y[data$train_id == "train"]
y_valid <- y[data$train_id == "test"]

set.seed(1)
sample(colnames(X), 25)
##  [1] "the german"      "raids"           "flooding"       
##  [4] "concerned about" "gave"            "turkish prime"  
##  [7] "attempted to"    "2013 s"          "nearby"         
## [10] "earthquake"      "video of"        "issue"          
## [13] "arrest s"        "cable"           "adoption"       
## [16] "the air"         "damaging"        "northeast"      
## [19] "page"            "enters"          "the mexican"    
## [22] "the people"      "once again"      "running"        
## [25] "broke"
model <- cv.glmnet(X_train, y_train, nfolds = 5, family = "gaussian")
plot(model)

data$Delta_pred_bigrams <- predict(model, newx = X, s=model$lambda[30])
sqrt(tapply((data$Delta_pred_bigrams - data$Delta)^2, data$train_id, mean))
##      test     train 
## 154.58068  90.15058

We arrive at an RMSE of 147 using bigrams, which is a lot better than our first approach.

Character shingles

How about considering character shingles of our headlines? Lets see how our model does using this new strategy.

token_list <- tokenize_character_shingles(data$all, n_min = 1, n = 3, strip_non_alphanum = FALSE)

token_df <- term_list_to_df(token_list)

X <- term_df_to_matrix(token_df, min_df = 0.01, max_df = 0.90,
                       scale = TRUE)

y <- data$Delta

X_train <- X[data$train_id == "train",]
X_valid <- X[data$train_id == "test",]
y_train <- y[data$train_id == "train"]
y_valid <- y[data$train_id == "test"]

# Let's see what the character shingles look like
set.seed(1)
sample(colnames(X), 25)
##  [1] "iva"  "tir"  "mie"  "1 h"  "vio"  "v h"  "b g"  "oit"  "900"  "eb"  
## [11] "pai"  "ory"  "apr"  "kid"  "8 h"  "nym"  "ckn"  "afp"  "kh"   "lst" 
## [21] " \nm" "sli"  "uru"  "lla"  "acr"
model <- cv.glmnet(X_train, y_train, nfolds = 5, family = "gaussian", alpha = 0.8)
data$Delta_pred_charshingles <- predict(model, newx = X, type = "response", s=model$lambda[30])
sqrt(tapply((data$Delta_pred_charshingles - data$Delta)^2, data$train_id, mean))

It seems like character shingles and bigrams give us a similar RMSE. Sad :(

Word embeddings and neural nets

To remind you of what a word embedding is (from Dr.Arnolds slides): A word embedding is nothing more than a compression of a one-hot representation and a dense hidden layer in a neural network.

words <- tokenize_words(data$all)

# vocabulary of terms we will allow in the model will be the top 10000 words in the headlines
vocab <- top_n(count(data_frame(word = unlist(words)), word), n = 10000)$word
## Selecting by n

Running 50 epochs gives us an RMSE of ~140, which is slightly better than our other models.

Convolutional neural nets

Lets use a CNN to see if we get better results.

model <- keras_model_sequential()
model %>%
  layer_embedding(
    input_dim = length(vocab) + 1,
    output_dim = 50,
    input_length = ncol(X)
    ) %>%

  layer_conv_1d(filters = 128, kernel_size = c(5)) %>%
  layer_global_average_pooling_1d() %>%
  layer_dropout(rate = 0.2) %>%

  layer_dense(256) %>%
  layer_activation("relu")%>%
  layer_dense(1) 

model %>% compile(
  loss = "mse",
  optimizer = optimizer_rmsprop(),
  metrics = c("mse")
)

Transfer Learning

Lets have a look at transfer learning to see if this gets us better results. Well use the fasttextM library for this.

y <- data$Label
text <- data[stri_length(data$all) > 100,]
words <- tokenize_words(text$all)
vocab <- top_n(count(data_frame(word = unlist(words)), word),
                n = 10000)$word
## Selecting by n
id <- lapply(words, function(v) match(v, vocab))
id <- lapply(id, function(v) v[!is.na(v)])
X <- pad_sequences(id, maxlen = 100)

X_words <- matrix(c("", vocab)[X + 1], nrow = nrow(X))
library(fasttextM)
ft_load_model("en")
X_embed <- ft_embed(as.vector(X_words), lang = "en")
X_embed[is.na(X_embed)] <- 0
X_embed <- array(X_embed, dim = c(nrow(X_words), ncol(X_words), 100))
model <- keras_model_sequential()
model %>%
  layer_lstm(units = 64,
             dropout = 0.2,
             recurrent_dropout = 0.2,
             return_sequences = FALSE,
             input_shape = dim(X_embed)[-1]) %>%
  layer_dense(units = 1, activation = 'relu')
model %>% compile(loss = 'mse',
                  optimizer = 'adam',
                  metrics = c('mse'))

X_train <- X_embed[data$train_id == "train",,]
X_valid <- X_embed[data$train_id == "valid",,]
y <- data$Delta
y_train <- y[data$train_id == "train"]
y_valid <- y[data$train_id == "valid"]

history <- model %>% fit(X_train, y_train,
              batch_size = 32,
              epochs = 10,
              validation_data = list(X_valid, y_valid))

plot(history)

data$Delta_pred_transfer <- predict(model, X_embed)
sqrt(tapply((data$Delta_pred_transfer - data$Delta)^2, data$train_id, mean))
##     test    train 
## 147.5274 139.0472

It seems as if the CNN and transfer learning models were the best of the lot, with accuracies of close to 55%.

Closing remarks

All of our models have an accuracy of a little over 50%, which is what random guessing would give us. Some reasons that these models cant give us a higher accuracy are:

  • The headline data that I used is pretty general since it encapsulates a wide range of topics that are not relevant to stock markets. Using financial news would definitely give us better results.
  • Since financial news may not occur as often as political news, it is difficult for a machine learning model to sift through the noise and pick our relevant words that might cause the Dow Jones index to rise/fall.

Fun fact!

It turns out that this strategy may have been used by hedge funds. From 2008-2010, it was observed that Berkshire-Hathaway stock would rise every time an Anne Hathaway movie would release. This could result from hedge funds using techniques similar to the ones Ive used above.
